data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class plus better assert methods. Your current code uses `Assert.IsTrue` for everything, which gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure, shows *both* values instead of just "false"
- **`CollectionAssert`** — purpose-built for collections:
  - `AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`
  - `AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
  - `Contains(collection, item)`
  - `AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same elements, same order
  - `AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order
  - `IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`
- **Add message strings** to `Assert.IsTrue` when you must use it (e.g., LINQ predicates), so failures are diagnosable

**If you want even richer assertions**, consider adding [FluentAssertions](https://fluentassertions.com):

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```
